<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="27" type="comments">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="27">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="27">
Based on currently known data, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Shaw &amp; van Noort" authorityYear="2022" class="Insecta" family="Proteaceae" genus="Dinapsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Dinapsis zulu" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zulu">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">Dinapsis zulu</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is associated with the forest biome, which is a naturally highly fragmented habitat in South Africa (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.2307/2845148" author="Lawes, MJ" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Biogeography" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" pagination="669 - 680" refId="B28" refString="Lawes, MJ, 1990. The distribution of the Samango monkey (Cercopithecus mitis erythrarchus Peters, 1852 and Cercopithecus mitis labiatus I. Geoffroy, 1843) and forest history in southern Africa. Journal of Biogeography 17 (6): 669 - 680, DOI: https://doi.org/10.2307/2845148" title="The distribution of the Samango monkey (Cercopithecus mitis erythrarchus Peters, 1852 and Cercopithecus mitis labiatus I. Geoffroy, 1843) and forest history in southern Africa." url="https://doi.org/10.2307/2845148" volume="17" year="1990">Lawes 1990</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/0-306-48417-X_24" author="Lawes, MJ" editor="Glenn, ME" journalOrPublisher="Springer, Boston, MA" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" pagination="375 - 392" refId="B29" refString="Lawes, MJ, 2004. Conservation of fragmented populations of Cercopithecus mitis in South Africa: the role of reintroduction, corridors and metapopulation ecology. In: Glenn, ME, Cords, M, Eds., The Guenons: diversity and adaptation in African monkeys. Springer, Boston, MA: 375 - 392, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1007/0-306-48417-X_24" title="Conservation of fragmented populations of Cercopithecus mitis in South Africa: the role of reintroduction, corridors and metapopulation ecology." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/0-306-48417-X_24" volumeTitle="The Guenons: diversity and adaptation in African monkeys." year="2004">2004</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1046/j.1365-2699.1999.00307.x" author="Eeley, HAC" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Biogeography" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" pagination="595 - 617" refId="B10" refString="Eeley, HAC, Lawes, MJ, Piper, SE, 1999. The influence of climate change on the distribution of indigenous forest in KwaZulu-Natal, South Africa. Journal of Biogeography 26 (3): 595 - 617, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1046/j.1365-2699.1999.00307.x" title="The influence of climate change on the distribution of indigenous forest in KwaZulu-Natal, South Africa." url="https://doi.org/10.1046/j.1365-2699.1999.00307.x" volume="26" year="1999">Eeley et al. 1999</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Mucina, L" journalOrPublisher="Strelitzia" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" pagination="584 - 614" refId="B42" refString="Mucina, L, Geldenhuys, CJ, 2006. Afrotemperate, subtropical and azonal forests. Strelitzia 19: 584 - 614" title="Afrotemperate, subtropical and azonal forests." volume="19" year="2006">Mucina and Geldenhuys 2006</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1365-2699.2007.01696.x" author="Lawes, MJ" journalOrPublisher="Springer, Boston, MA" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" refId="B30" refString="Lawes, MJ, Eeley, HAC, Findlay, NJ, Forbes, D, 2007. Resilient forest faunal communities in South Africa: A legacy of palaeoclimatic change and extinction filtering? Journal of Biogeography 34(7): 1246-1264. https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1365-2699.2007.01696.x" title="Resilient forest faunal communities in South Africa: A legacy of palaeoclimatic change and extinction filtering? Journal of Biogeography 34 (7): 1246 - 1264." url="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1365-2699.2007.01696.x" year="2007">Lawes et al. 2007</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.actao.2019.103506" author="Deng, J-Y" journalOrPublisher="ZooKeys" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" refId="B9" refString="Deng, J-Y, van Noort, S, Compton, SG, Chen, Y, Greeff, JM, 2020. The genetic consequences of habitat specificity for fig trees in southern African fragmented forests. Acta Oecologica 102: e103506. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.actao.2019.103506" title="The genetic consequences of habitat specificity for fig trees in southern African fragmented forests. Acta Oecologica 102: e 103506." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.actao.2019.103506" year="2020">Deng et al. 2020</bibRefCitation>
), and hence the species distribution is likely to follow suit. The current distribution pattern is likely to be an artefact of under-sampling and we expect the species to be recorded from further forest localities in both provinces. While the main body colour is black to dark brown in most specimens, the specimens from Tsitsikamma have lighter tones ranging from reddish brown to yellowish brown. This might be due to different environmental conditions (the Tsitsikamma forest is more temperate) during their development, or they might be specimens that were collected soon after emergence before the cuticle had fully tanned and darkened.
</paragraph>
